data.content:
## What breaks

In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), the **sync-over-async compatibility shim for the Cosmos DB provider is removed**. The temporary opt-in you configured in .NET 10 no longer exists.

All four methods will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime because the Cosmos DB provider **only supports async operations natively**. Calls like `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` have no synchronous path.

## The fix — migrate to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `Add()` stays synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory.
- Every method that hits Cosmos (queries + `SaveChanges`) must be `async`/`await`.
- Callers need to be updated to `await` these methods, which typically means propagating `async` up the call chain (controllers, services, etc.).
